<p><b>Vasiliy Anatolyevich Lomachenko</b> (also spelled <b>Vasyl Anatoliyovych Lomachenko</b>; <a href="/wiki/Ukrainian_language" title="Ukrainian language">Ukrainian</a>: <span lang="uk"> </span>, <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1177148991">.mw-parser-output .IPA-label-small{font-size:85%}.mw-parser-output .references .IPA-label-small,.mw-parser-output .infobox .IPA-label-small,.mw-parser-output .navbox .IPA-label-small{font-size:100%}</style><span class="IPA-label IPA-label-small">IPA:</span> <span class="IPA nowrap" lang="uk-Latn-fonipa"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA/Ukrainian" title="Help:IPA/Ukrainian">&#91;wsl<span class="wrap"> </span>lomtnko&#93;</a></span>; born 17 February 1988) is a Ukrainian former <a href="/wiki/Professional_boxer" class="mw-redirect" title="Professional boxer">professional boxer</a> who competed between 2013 and 2024. He has held multiple <a href="/wiki/Triple_champion#Boxing" title="Triple champion">world championships in three weight classes</a>, including the <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Organization" title="World Boxing Organization">World Boxing Organization</a> (WBO) <a href="/wiki/Featherweight" title="Featherweight">featherweight</a> title from 2014 to 2016, the WBO <a href="/wiki/Super_featherweight" title="Super featherweight">super featherweight</a> title from 2016 to 2018, the <a href="/wiki/Unified_champion" class="mw-redirect" title="Unified champion">unified</a> <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Association" title="World Boxing Association">World Boxing Association</a> (WBA) (<a href="/wiki/WBA_(Super)" class="mw-redirect" title="WBA (Super)">Super version</a>), <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Council" title="World Boxing Council">World Boxing Council</a> (WBC), WBO, and <a href="/wiki/The_Ring_(magazine)" title="The Ring (magazine)"><i>Ring magazine</i></a> <a href="/wiki/Lightweight" title="Lightweight">lightweight</a> titles from 2018 to 2020, and the <a href="/wiki/International_Boxing_Federation" title="International Boxing Federation">International Boxing Federation</a> (IBF) lightweight title from 2024 to 2025.
</p><p>Lomachenko is one of the most successful <a href="/wiki/Amateur_boxer" class="mw-redirect" title="Amateur boxer">amateur boxers</a> of all time and often considered to be the greatest, possessing a record of 396 wins and 1 loss, with that loss avenged twice.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>4<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Competing in the featherweight and lightweight divisions, he won a silver medal at the <a href="/wiki/2007_World_Amateur_Boxing_Championships" class="mw-redirect" title="2007 World Amateur Boxing Championships">2007 World Championships</a>, gold at the <a href="/wiki/2008_European_Amateur_Boxing_Championships" title="2008 European Amateur Boxing Championships">2008 European Championships</a>, consecutive gold at the <a href="/wiki/2008_Olympics" class="mw-redirect" title="2008 Olympics">2008</a> and <a href="/wiki/2012_Olympics" class="mw-redirect" title="2012 Olympics">2012 Olympics</a>, and consecutive gold at the <a href="/wiki/2009_World_Amateur_Boxing_Championships" class="mw-redirect" title="2009 World Amateur Boxing Championships">2009</a> and <a href="/wiki/2011_World_Amateur_Boxing_Championships" class="mw-redirect" title="2011 World Amateur Boxing Championships">2011 World Championships</a>.
</p><p>Making his professional debut in 2013, Lomachenko tied the record with Thailand's <a href="/wiki/Saensak_Muangsurin" title="Saensak Muangsurin">Saensak Muangsurin</a> for winning a world title in the fewest professional fights, becoming the <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Organization" title="World Boxing Organization">World Boxing Organization</a> (WBO) featherweight champion in his third fight. He is known for his exceptional hand speed, timing, accuracy, creativity, athleticism, defence and footwork.
</p><p>He has won several awards by media outlets throughout his career. <i>The Ring</i> and <a href="/wiki/ESPN" title="ESPN">ESPN</a> named him Prospect of the Year in 2013; <a href="/wiki/CBS_Sports" title="CBS Sports">CBS Sports</a> named him Boxer of the Year in 2016;<sup id="cite&#95;ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>5<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> <a href="/wiki/HBO_Sports" class="mw-redirect" title="HBO Sports">HBO Sports</a> named him Boxer of the Year in 2016 and in 2017;<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:9&#95;6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:9-6"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>6<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-:10&#95;7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:10-7"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>7<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> and the <a href="/wiki/Boxing_Writers_Association_of_America" title="Boxing Writers Association of America">Boxing Writers Association of America</a> and <i>The Ring</i> named him Fighter of the Year in 2017.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>8<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On June 5th, 2025, Lomachenko announced his retirement from professional boxing at the age of 37.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:6&#95;9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-9"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>9<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Early_life">Early life</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Early life"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Lomachenko was coached by his father <a href="/wiki/Anatoly_Lomachenko" title="Anatoly Lomachenko">Anatoly Lomachenko</a> from a young age. He claims that if his father had not been a boxing coach he probably would have chosen to play <a href="/wiki/Ice_hockey" title="Ice hockey">ice hockey</a> professionally.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-personal&#95;10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-personal-10"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>10<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> According to <a href="/wiki/Bob_Arum" title="Bob Arum">Bob Arum</a> in 2017, Lomachenko's father did not let him train for boxing until he attended traditional <a href="/wiki/Ukrainian_dance" title="Ukrainian dance">Ukrainian dance</a> classes. He then went on to gymnastics before finally getting into the ring.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>11<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Amateur_career">Amateur career</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Amateur career"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>At the 2007 World Championships in Chicago, he won silver by beating <a href="/wiki/Abner_Cotto" title="Abner Cotto">Abner Cotto</a> in the first round, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Theodoros_Papazov&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Theodoros Papazov (page does not exist)">Theodoros Papazov</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mikhail_Bernadski" class="mw-redirect" title="Mikhail Bernadski">Mikhail Bernadski</a>, <a href="/wiki/Arturo_Santos_Reyes" title="Arturo Santos Reyes">Arturo Santos Reyes</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Li_Yang_(boxer)" title="Li Yang (boxer)">Li Yang</a> in the semifinal to reach fellow southpaw and Russian favorite <a href="/wiki/Albert_Selimov" title="Albert Selimov">Albert Selimov</a>, to whom he lost 1116. This was the only loss in Lomachenko's amateur career.
</p><p>Lomachenko won gold at the 2008 Olympic Games in <a href="/wiki/Beijing" title="Beijing">Beijing</a>. He beat his five opponents by an astonishing 45 point margin, outscoring them 5813, en route to his first gold medal at the senior level. He was subsequently named the outstanding boxer of the tournament and awarded the <a href="/wiki/Val_Barker_Trophy" class="mw-redirect" title="Val Barker Trophy">Val Barker Trophy</a>. Additionally, he won gold again that year to also become continental champion at the European Championships in <a href="/wiki/Liverpool" title="Liverpool">Liverpool</a>.
</p><p>He won gold at the 2009 World Championships in <a href="/wiki/Milan" title="Milan">Milan</a>. He then competed as a lightweight at the 2011 World Championships in <a href="/wiki/Baku" title="Baku">Baku</a> after <a href="/wiki/International_Boxing_Association_(amateur)" class="mw-redirect" title="International Boxing Association (amateur)">AIBA</a> removed the featherweight division. There, he won his second consecutive gold medal to become a two-weight world champion.
</p><p>Following a forced move up to lightweight, he won his second consecutive Olympic gold medal at the 2012 Olympic Games in London to become a rare two-weight Olympic champion.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>12<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> He defeated <a href="/wiki/Han_Soon-Chul" class="mw-redirect" title="Han Soon-Chul">Han Soon-Chul</a> of <a href="/wiki/South_Korea_at_the_2012_Summer_Olympics" title="South Korea at the 2012 Summer Olympics">South Korea</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Boxing_at_the_2012_Summer_Olympics_%E2%80%93_Men%27s_lightweight" title="Boxing at the 2012 Summer Olympics Men&#39;s lightweight">final</a>, <span class="nowrap">199</span>, and was a strong candidate to win the Val Barker Trophy for a second time in what would have historically been an unprecedented feat. Ultimately, he was edged out by welterweight gold medal winner, <a href="/wiki/Serik_Sapiyev" title="Serik Sapiyev">Serik Sapiyev</a>, of <a href="/wiki/Kazakhstan" title="Kazakhstan">Kazakhstan</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>13<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>He finished his extensive amateur career with an impressive record of 396 wins and only 1 loss, to <a href="/wiki/Albert_Selimov" title="Albert Selimov">Albert Selimov</a>, which was avenged twice.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-BLH1012&#95;14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BLH1012-14"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>14<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>15<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In November 2017, boxing website <i>The Sweet Science</i> conducted a readers' poll, which ran for several weeks, to determine the amateur boxer regarded by the public majority as the all-time best. Alongside Lomachenko, the five other standout finalists selected were: <a href="/wiki/L%C3%A1szl%C3%B3_Papp" title="Lszl Papp">Lszl Papp</a>, <a href="/wiki/Te%C3%B3filo_Stevenson" title="Tefilo Stevenson">Tefilo Stevenson</a>, <a href="/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Sav%C3%B3n" title="Flix Savn">Flix Savn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mark_Breland" title="Mark Breland">Mark Breland</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Guillermo_Rigondeaux" title="Guillermo Rigondeaux">Guillermo Rigondeaux</a>. While none were able to claim the majority vote, Lomachenko won a <a href="/wiki/Plurality_(voting)" title="Plurality (voting)">plurality</a>, having led the poll with nearly one-third of the total votes cast.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>16<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>

<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="World_Series_of_Boxing">World Series of Boxing</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: World Series of Boxing"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Prior to turning professional, Lomachenko competed in the <a href="/wiki/Lightweight" title="Lightweight">lightweight</a> division of the <a href="/wiki/World_Series_of_Boxing" title="World Series of Boxing">World Series of Boxing</a> (WSB) from January to May 2013. Some outlets would later claim that the six fights Lomachenko had in this tournament should have counted towards his professional record, due to WSB being professional boxing by law, with no <a href="/wiki/Headgear_(martial_arts)" title="Headgear (martial arts)">headgear</a> and rounds being scored using the <a href="/wiki/10-point_must_system" class="mw-redirect" title="10-point must system">ten-point must system</a> according to the regulations set by professional boxing commissions that license the boxers, promoters, and officials.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>20<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Professional_career">Professional career</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Professional career"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Featherweight">Featherweight</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Featherweight"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After winning his second Olympic gold medal, Lomachenko made the decision to turn professional. After meeting with several fight promoters, he signed a contract to fight for <a href="/wiki/Top_Rank" title="Top Rank">Top Rank</a>. Lomachenko made his professional debut in United States on 12 October 2013 as part of the undercard to <a href="/wiki/Timothy_Bradley_vs._Juan_Manuel_M%C3%A1rquez" title="Timothy Bradley vs. Juan Manuel Mrquez">Timothy Bradley vs. Juan Manuel Mrquez</a>, defeating Mexican fighter Jos Ramirez with a fourth-round knockout.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-BLH1012&#95;14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BLH1012-14"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>14<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Salido">Lomachenko vs. Salido</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Salido"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Orlando_Salido_vs._Vasiliy_Lomachenko" title="Orlando Salido vs. Vasiliy Lomachenko">Orlando Salido vs. Vasiliy Lomachenko</a></div>
<p>Lomachenko attempted to make history by winning a world championship in his second fight and breaking <a href="/wiki/Saensak_Muangsurin" title="Saensak Muangsurin">Saensak Muangsurin</a>'s record, who won a junior welterweight world title in his third pro fight in 1975. He challenged veteran boxer <a href="/wiki/Orlando_Salido" title="Orlando Salido">Orlando Salido</a> for <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Organization" title="World Boxing Organization">World Boxing Organization</a>'s featherweight title. The title became vacant after Salido failed to make weight, weighed in <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027" /><span class="frac">128<span class="sr-only">+</span><span class="num">1</span>&#8260;<span class="den">4</span></span> pounds, over the 126 pound limit. On fight night, he rehydrated to 147 pounds, which was equivalent to the welterweight limit. All of which were still legal since there were no rehydration clauses disclosed in the contract. The fight took place in front of 7,323 at the <a href="/wiki/Alamodome" title="Alamodome">Alamodome</a> in <a href="/wiki/San_Antonio,_Texas" class="mw-redirect" title="San Antonio, Texas">San Antonio, Texas</a>, on 1 March 2014.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>21<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko would earn $631,000, for what was his second professional bout.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:1&#95;22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-22"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>22<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Lomachenko seemed to shy away from engaging Salido throughout most of the fight, probably due to Salido landing numerous low blows and head-butts that the referee failed to call and/or deduct a point. A total of 52 low blows can easily be counted throughout the bout, something that his opponent exploited. A late surge, which saw him injure Salido in the final round, was unable to change the final result, losing by <a href="/wiki/Split_decision" title="Split decision">split decision</a>. Two judges had it for Salido 116112 and 115113, while the third had it for Lomachenko 115113. Lomachenko, for his part, stated he felt the decision was fair and accepted blame for not following through with his corner's game plan, promising to learn from the experience and come back stronger.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-ESPN&#95;23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ESPN-23"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>23<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>24<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The referee of the fight, Laurence Cole, was roundly criticized by many boxing media outlets for his seemingly ignoring the very many foul blows by Salido, and his perceived failure to properly conduct the match.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>25<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>26<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>27<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Russell_Jr.">Lomachenko vs. Russell Jr.</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Russell Jr."><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The WBO title remained vacant due to Salido not making weight. On 20 March 2014 the WBO contacted <a href="/wiki/Golden_Boy_Promotions" title="Golden Boy Promotions">Golden Boy Promotions</a> and <a href="/wiki/Top_Rank" title="Top Rank">Top Rank</a> to make them aware that they had 30 days to negotiate a fight between Lomachenko and <a href="/wiki/Gary_Russell_Jr." title="Gary Russell Jr.">Gary Russell Jr.</a> (240, 14 KO) for the vacant WBO featherweight title. In an interview, WBO President Paco Valcarcel said that the fight should take place no later than July 2014.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>28<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Purse bids were scheduled which Golden Boy won with a bid of $1,052,500, while Top Rank bid $1,050,000.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>29<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko was entitled to $631,350 (60%) and Russell Jr. was entitled to $420,900 (40%). Golden Boy CEO <a href="/wiki/Richard_Schaefer" title="Richard Schaefer">Richard Schaefer</a> challenged Lomachenko's residency. According to the WBO, "If the fight is held in the country of origin, residence or nationality of one of the contenders, the resident contestant shall receive 40 percent and his opponent shall receive 60 percent off the total purse offered." Schaefer claimed Lomachenko resided in <a href="/wiki/Marina_del_Rey,_California" title="Marina del Rey, California">Marina del Rey, California</a>. It was later ascertained that Lomachenko had rented a home in California to live in while training, while Ukraine remained his permanent residence.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>30<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>31<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The fight took place on 21 June at the <a href="/wiki/StubHub_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="StubHub Center">StubHub Center</a> in <a href="/wiki/Carson,_California" title="Carson, California">Carson, California</a>. Lomachenko defeated Russell Jr. via twelve-round <a href="/wiki/Majority_decision" title="Majority decision">majority decision</a> to win the vacant <a href="/wiki/World_Boxing_Organization" title="World Boxing Organization">WBO</a> featherweight title. Judge Lisa Giampa scored the fight a 114114 draw, but judges Max DeLuca and Pat Russell scored the fight 116112 in favor of Lomachenko.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>32<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko used his power and swift skills to maintain control of the fight until the final bell. Lomachenko began to hurt Russell Jr. more in the later rounds with power shots. Russell Jr. landed only 10% of his punches thrown, with a lot of combinations being missed or blocked. Lomachenko landed 183 of 597 punches thrown (31%) and Russell Jr. landed 83 of his 806 thrown.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>33<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> With this victory, Lomachenko joined <a href="/wiki/Saensak_Muangsurin" title="Saensak Muangsurin">Saensak Muangsurin</a> as the only other boxer to have won a world title in the quickest amount of time since turning professional, accomplishing the feat in just his third professional bout.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>34<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>35<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>36<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight averaged 578,000 viewers.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>37<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Piriyapinyo">Lomachenko vs. Piriyapinyo</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Piriyapinyo"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Lomachenko made his first title defense against <a href="/wiki/Mandatory_challenger" title="Mandatory challenger">mandatory challenger</a> <a href="/wiki/Chonlatarn_Piriyapinyo" title="Chonlatarn Piriyapinyo">Chonlatarn Piriyapinyo</a> of Thailand. This fight took place on the undercard of <a href="/wiki/Manny_Pacquiao_vs._Chris_Algieri" title="Manny Pacquiao vs. Chris Algieri">Manny Pacquiao vs. Chris Algieri</a> on <a href="/wiki/HBO_pay-per-view" class="mw-redirect" title="HBO pay-per-view">HBO PPV</a> bout on November 22, 2014, at the <a href="/wiki/Cotai_Arena" class="mw-redirect" title="Cotai Arena">Cotai Arena</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Venetian_Macao" title="The Venetian Macao">Venetian Resort</a> in <a href="/wiki/Macau" title="Macau">Macao</a>. Although Piriyapinyo's record of 52 wins and 1 loss made the fight sound challenging for Lomachenko, the only time he stepped up in his 11-year career was in 2012 against <a href="/wiki/Chris_John_(boxer)" title="Chris John (boxer)">Chris John</a>, which he lost via unanimous decision.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>38<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko handled his opponent easily, hurting him a few times and scoring a knockdown at the end of the fourth round. In the seventh round, Lomachenko stopped using his left hand; it was later confirmed that he injured that hand. Lomachenko won a unanimous decision with the scores of 120107 on all three of the judges' scorecards.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>39<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>40<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko landed 368 of 1006 punches thrown (37%) and Piriyapinyo landed 94 of his 501 thrown (19%).<sup id="cite&#95;ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>41<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Rodrguez"><span id="Lomachenko_vs._Rodr.C3.ADguez"></span>Lomachenko vs. Rodrguez</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Rodrguez"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It was announced prior to Lomachenko's mandatory fight against Piriyapinyo that the winner would next fight 28 year old Puerto Rican boxer <a href="/wiki/Gamalier_Rodr%C3%ADguez" title="Gamalier Rodrguez">Gamalier Rodrguez</a>. Rodriguez earned the title shot after knocking out Martin Cardona.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>42<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight was announced to take place on 2 May 2015 on the under-card of <a href="/wiki/Floyd_Mayweather_Jr._vs._Manny_Pacquiao" title="Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao">Mayweather-Pacquiao</a> at the <a href="/wiki/MGM_Grand_Garden_Arena" title="MGM Grand Garden Arena">MGM Grand Garden Arena</a>. Prior to the fight, Rodriguez was on a 17-fight winning streak dating back to 2010, where the fight resulted in a first round technical draw.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>43<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Top Rank announced before the fight that Lomachenko had signed a five-year contract extension. On fight night, Lomachenko retained his WBO title against Rodriguez via a ninth-round KO victory. Lomachenko's speed and precision was too much for Rodriguez, who took a knee twice in the fight, once in the seventh and again in the ninth, which ended the bout. He was also docked a point by referee in fifth round for a low blow. Lomachenko landed 227 of 586 punches thrown (39%) compared to Rodriguez who landed only 55 of 285 (19%). After the fight, Lomachenko spoke through a translator about his performance, "I was just boxing for the fans, having a good time out there." Top Rank were hoping to match Lomachenko with then-WBA featherweight champion <a href="/wiki/Nicholas_Walters" title="Nicholas Walters">Nicholas Walters</a> in a unification fight.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>44<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>45<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko had a $750,000 purse for the defence.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:1&#95;22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-22"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>22<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Koasicha">Lomachenko vs. Koasicha</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Koasicha"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Lomachenko next fought on the <a href="/wiki/Timothy_Bradley" title="Timothy Bradley">Tim Bradley</a> vs. <a href="/wiki/Brandon_R%C3%ADos" title="Brandon Ros">Brandon Ros</a> undercard on <a href="/wiki/HBO" title="HBO">HBO</a> against #7 WBO ranked 24 year old Romulo Koasicha. The fight took place on 7 November 2015 at the <a href="/wiki/Mandalay_Bay" title="Mandalay Bay">Mandalay Bay Resort &amp; Casino</a> in <a href="/wiki/Paradise,_Nevada" title="Paradise, Nevada">Paradise, Nevada</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>46<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> He overwhelmed, dominated and stopped Koasicha in the tenth round on a body shot. In the post fight interview, Lomachenko told of how he wanted to put on a good show, "I was just having fun in there, "If I really wanted to knock him out, I would have done it earlier. I was having a good time, but I knew the end would be on a body shot. I just didn't know which one." Lomachenko earned a career high $750,000 for the fight and out landed Koasicha by 259 punches. CompuBox stats showed that Lomachenko dominated throughout, landing 334 of his 717 punches thrown (47%). Koasicha only managed to land 75 of 607 (12%) and earned $35,000 for the loss. The loss ended Koasicha's run of 4 straight wins and he suffered his first stoppage defeat.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>47<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>48<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>49<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Junior_lightweight">Junior lightweight</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Junior lightweight"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Martinez">Lomachenko vs. Martinez</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Martinez"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Following a third successful defense, Lomachenko, still the reigning WBO featherweight champion decided to move up weight to junior lightweight to challenge <a href="/wiki/Rom%C3%A1n_Mart%C3%ADnez_(boxer)" title="Romn Martnez (boxer)">Romn Martnez</a> for his <a href="/wiki/WBO_Super_Featherweight_Champion" class="mw-redirect" title="WBO Super Featherweight Champion">WBO title</a> on 11 June 2016 at the <a href="/wiki/The_Theater_at_Madison_Square_Garden" title="The Theater at Madison Square Garden">Madison Square Garden Theater</a>. Martinez was coming off a <a href="/wiki/Floyd_Mayweather_Jr._vs._Andre_Berto" title="Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Andre Berto">draw against Orlando Salido in September 2015</a>, after he controversially defeated him in their first fight in April 2015 for the WBO title.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>50<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko became the fastest boxer to win a world title in two weight divisions knocking out Martinez in the 5th round of the world title fight. Lomachenko dominated the fight from the start with superior footwork, hand speed and slick punching from different angles. According to <a href="/wiki/CompuBox" title="CompuBox">CompuBox</a>, Lomachenko out-landed Martinez 87 to 34. After the fight, Lomachenko called out <a href="/wiki/Orlando_Salido" title="Orlando Salido">Orlando Salido</a>, "Hey Salido, I'm ready to fight you at any time, before the Vargas fight, I told him to win the fight but I never told him I wasn't going to fight him if he didn't, so let's do it. I want to revenge Salido for my fans and give them a win over him."<sup id="cite&#95;ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>51<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko was paid $850,000 for the bout, at the time a career-high purse.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:1&#95;22-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-22"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>22<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Walters">Lomachenko vs. Walters</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Walters"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After failing to make the fight happen earlier in the year, <a href="/wiki/Top_Rank" title="Top Rank">Top Rank</a> vice president Carl Moretti confirmed on September 28 that Lomachenko would defend his WBO title against 30 year old unbeaten Jamaican boxer <a href="/wiki/Nicholas_Walters" title="Nicholas Walters">Nicholas Walters</a> at <a href="/wiki/Cosmopolitan_of_Las_Vegas" title="Cosmopolitan of Las Vegas">The Cosmopolitan</a> in <a href="/wiki/Las_Vegas" title="Las Vegas">Las Vegas</a> on 26 November on HBO.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>52<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In previous negotiations, Walters turned down a career-high $550,000 purse, even after Lomachenko offered him a further $300,000 from his own purse if Walters won. HBO provided the remainder of Walter's purse for the fight to go ahead. The event marked Bob Arum's 2,000th promoted card, as well as celebrating his 50th anniversary as a promoter.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>53<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>After Lomachenko dominated the first six rounds with his movement, he threw more combination punches in the seventh which left Walters visibly shaken. Lomachenko won the fight after Walters retired on his stool at the end of the seventh round. Upon returning to his corner, Walters got up and walked to referee Tony Weeks, where he reiterated twice he did not want to continue. A lot of boos followed the confirmation of the fight result as Walters seemed to back himself up for not returning for round 8, blaming his inactivity in the ring, "Listen to me, if I get the chance to fight two or three fights leading up to this fight, I'll definitely take him on in different circumstances where we are more active and definitely beat him but it was all him tonight... he fought me with three fights this year. So it was all him tonight... Nothing take away from him, he's a very good fighter, I learned a lot from fighting him and it was seven rounds of beautiful boxing until my corner decided to end it."<sup id="cite&#95;ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>54<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>55<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>CompuBox stats showed Lomachenko landed 114 of 437 punches thrown (26 percent) while Walters landed 49 of 264 (19 percent). Lomachenko earned his first $1 million purse. Following the post fight, Arum told ESPN, he would like to make a rematch with Salido next, followed by a lightweight title fight against <a href="/wiki/Terry_Flanagan_(boxer)" title="Terry Flanagan (boxer)">Terry Flanagan</a> and then a super fight with <a href="/wiki/Manny_Pacquiao" title="Manny Pacquiao">Manny Pacquiao</a>. The fight drew 761,000 viewers on HBO.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>56<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>57<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Sosa">Lomachenko vs. Sosa</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Sosa"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On 2 February 2017, Bob Arum spoke to <a href="/wiki/ESPN" title="ESPN">ESPN</a>. After failing to make a match up with WBA (Super) champion <a href="/wiki/Jezreel_Corrales" title="Jezreel Corrales">Jezreel Corrales</a>, he announced Lomachenko's next fight would take place on 8 April at the <a href="/wiki/MGM_National_Harbor" title="MGM National Harbor">MGM National Harbor</a> in Washington, D.C., in a super featherweight unification against <a href="/wiki/List_of_WBA_world_champions" title="List of WBA world champions">WBA (Regular) champion</a> <a href="/wiki/Jason_Sosa" title="Jason Sosa">Jason Sosa</a>. This would have been Sosa's third defence of his secondary title, but on 16 February, he vacated the title.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>58<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>59<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>60<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko weighed 129.6 pounds. Sosa weighed in at 130.4 pounds, he then stripped down naked and still over weighed at 130.2 and was given the time to trim the extra weight.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>61<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> He later returned to the Maryland commission's scale and successfully made weight exactly 130 pounds allowing himself to challenge for the WBO title.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>62<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight headlined <a href="/wiki/HBO_World_Championship_Boxing" title="HBO World Championship Boxing">HBO <i>World Championship Boxing</i></a>. In front of a sell-out crowd of 2,828, mostly Ukrainian, Lomachenko successfully retained his WBO title for a second time after Sosa failed to return for round 10 when his trainer pulled him out. The bout was similar to Lomachenko's previous fight with Walters, who also pulled out. Lomachenko's flashy style and fast combinations won him the rounds. Sosa appeared more hurt in round 8 when he was hit hard on the body.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>63<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Sosa was the most successful opponent Lomachenko had fought since Salido in terms of landing punches. He landed 68 of his 286 thrown (24%). Lomachenko landed 275 of 696 punches (40%). Sosa's trainer, Raul Rivas explained why he pulled him out of the fight, "It was an accumulation of too many punches. I didn't want to get Jason hurt. He was out of the fight." Lomachenko said he wanted to follow this victory by only fighting current world champions at super featherweight for a chance to unify the division or he would move up lightweight.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>64<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko's purse for the fight was $800,000.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-:1&#95;22-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-22"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>22<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight peaked at 886,000 viewers <a href="/wiki/HBO" title="HBO">HBO</a> and averaged 832,000 viewers. These numbers showed an increase in viewership for Lomachenko from his last fight on HBO against Walters.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>65<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>66<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Marriaga">Lomachenko vs. Marriaga</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Marriaga"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>On 30 June 2017 Top Rank announced that a deal was in place for Lomachenko to make a third defense of his WBO title against Colombian former featherweight world title challenger <a href="/wiki/Miguel_Marriaga_(boxer)" title="Miguel Marriaga (boxer)">Miguel Marriaga</a>, who was coming off a loss and moving up to super featherweight. It was confirmed that the fight would take place live on <a href="/wiki/ESPN" title="ESPN">ESPN</a> on August 5, 2017, at the <a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Theater" class="mw-redirect" title="Microsoft Theater">Microsoft Theater</a> in Los Angeles.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>67<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Carl Moretti of Top Rank stated that Salido had initially turned down a $720,000 purse to fight Lomachenko in a rematch. Even after negotiations to meet his financial needs, Salido still denied the offer due to other problems, mentioning weight and hand issues.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>68<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>69<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In front of 4,102 people, Lomachenko dominated the fight from the opening bell and proved too much for Marriaga, dropping him twice in the fight, before Marriaga's corner stopped the fight after round 7. Lomachenko retained his WBO title for the third time. The first knockdown came towards the end of the third round when Lomachenko landed a straight left to Marriaga, who was off balance. Marriaga got up straight away and didn't appear hurt. In the fourth round, an accidental clash of heads opened up a cut above Lomachenko's left eye. In the following round, Lomachenko protested to referee Jack Reiss, claiming he was being hit low and headbutted. In the seventh round, Lomachenko landed body shots and uppercuts, eventually dropping Marriaga for the second time with a left hook at 2 minutes and 59 seconds of round 7. Marriaga beat the count and walked towards his corner. The referee waved an end to the fight moments later. Although it was a corner retirement, the <a href="/wiki/California_State_Athletic_Commission" title="California State Athletic Commission">California State Athletic Commission</a> ruled it a KO win.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>70<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko earned a $750,000 purse for the fight, compared to the $50,000 received by Marriaga.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>71<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the post fight interviews, Marriaga praised Lomachenko, "He dominated the fight. I connected with some good punches, but I couldn't get the result I was looking for. I wanted to continue the fight, but my corner stopped the fight. He basically overwhelmed me with pressure." Bob Arum also showed his admiration of Lomachenko, comparing him to former heavyweight world champion and legend <a href="/wiki/Muhammad_Ali" title="Muhammad Ali">Muhammad Ali</a>, who had 27 of his professional fight promoted by Arum. He said "I never saw anything like this. He's unbelievable. Not only does he have the knowledge, he has the skill set that I've never seen before. Fast, reflexes, everything and he really entertains. Who else did that? Muhammad Ali."<sup id="cite&#95;ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>72<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>73<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight averaged 728,000 viewers on ESPN. The move from HBO to ESPN was done to expose Lomachenko and gain more viewership, but was down by 104,000 compared to Lomachenko's last fight against Sosa on HBO. Viewership was adversely affected by a channel switch when the broadcast began and the time at which their main event started.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>74<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Rigondeaux">Lomachenko vs. Rigondeaux</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Rigondeaux"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Vasiliy_Lomachenko_vs._Guillermo_Rigondeaux" title="Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Guillermo Rigondeaux">Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Guillermo Rigondeaux</a></div>
<p>On 6 August, Arum stated that Lomachenko would fight for a third time in 2017, likely on 9 or 23 December. When asked who the potential options were, Arum stated, "Well, there's a few guys. (Guillermo) <a href="/wiki/Guillermo_Rigondeaux" title="Guillermo Rigondeaux">Rigondeaux</a> if he answers Dino (Duva's) call. There's (Orlando) <a href="/wiki/Orlando_Salido" title="Orlando Salido">Salido</a>, who's sniffing around and the third is (Miguel) <a href="/wiki/Miguel_Berchelt" title="Miguel Berchelt">Berchelt</a>." Arum also mentioned lightweight contender <a href="/wiki/Raymundo_Beltr%C3%A1n" class="mw-redirect" title="Raymundo Beltrn">Ray Beltrn</a>, but said he would like to capture a world title at lightweight before a potential fight with Lomachenko.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>75<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Salido informed his manager Sean Gibbons, that he had no issues with fighting Lomachenko in December. Gibbons believed Lomachenko needed Salido more than Salido would need Lomanchenko, as Lomachenko was looking to raise TV ratings and sell out a 10,000 capacity arena.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>76<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 14 August, Arum spoke to <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times" title="Los Angeles Times">LA Times</a> and confirmed either Rigondeaux or Salido would be Lomachenko's next opponent. He stated if the bout with Rigondeaux was made, it would likely take place at the <a href="/wiki/Madison_Square_Garden" title="Madison Square Garden">Madison Square Garden Theatre</a> and a potential rematch with Salido would take place in Los Angeles.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>77<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>On 21 August Arum stated the Lomachenko and Rigondeaux camps were closing in on finalizing a deal for December 9. A fight with the two-weight world champion and reigning <a href="/wiki/Super_bantamweight" title="Super bantamweight">super bantamweight</a> title holder, a two-time Olympic Gold Medalist and one of the most successful amateur boxers ever, would take place at 130 pounds.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>78<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight was officially confirmed on 15 September.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>79<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> It was since confirmed that the fight would in fact be at the Theater, headlining an ESPN televised card.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>80<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 18 November, Carl Moretti of Top Rank revealed a re-hydration clause on the contract. Both fighters agreed to weigh in at 09:00 on the morning of the fight, where they would not be able to exceed 138 pounds. Any fighter over the limit would face a penalty of more than $10,000.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>81<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On fight night, Lomachenko weighed 137.4 pounds and Rigondeaux weighed 130 pounds.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>82<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In front of a sell-out crowd of 5,102 at the Theater, Lomachenko retained his WBO title, dominating the fight with superior boxing skills, forcing Rigondeaux to retire on his stool after round 6. Rigondeaux stated he had broken the top of his left hand in round two, which was the reason he did not come out for round 7. Rigondeax became Lomachenko's fourth consecutive opponent to retire on his stool. The loss also marked the first time Rigondeaux had lost since 2003, when he was still an amateur. At the time of stoppage, Lomachenko was ahead on all three judges' scorecards, 6053, 5954, and 5954.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>83<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the post-fight interviews, Lomachenko was asked about Rigondeaux being his fourth consecutive opponent to retire on his stool, to which Lomachenko joked, "Maybe I should change my second name, now my name is 'No Mas Chenko'."<sup id="cite&#95;ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>84<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> He also went on to say, "This is not his weight, so it's not a big win for me. But he's a good fighter. He's got great skills. I adjusted to his style, low blows and all." Speaking to an interpreter, Rigondeaux said, "I lost, no excuses. I injured the top of my left hand in the second round. He's a very technical fighter. He's explosive. I'm gonna come back because that's what I do. The weight was not a factor in this fight. It was the injury to my hand." According to CompuBox statistics, Lomachenko landed 55 of 339 punches thrown (16%) and Rigondeax landed 15 of his 178 thrown (8%), landing no more than 3 punches per round. For the fight, Lomachenko was guaranteed a purse of $1.2 million whereas Rigondeaux earned a $400,000 purse.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>85<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On December 12, Dino Duva of Roc Nation Sport, confirmed that Rigondeaux had bruised his hand and not fractured it, as initially stated.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-86" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-86"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>86<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The card averaged 1.73 million viewers on ESPN, which did not include ESPN Deportes or the online streaming service.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>87<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id="Lightweight">Lightweight</h3><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Lightweight"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <i><a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times" title="Los Angeles Times">Los Angeles Times</a></i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">&#39;</span> Lance Pugmire was told by Bob Arum on 26 January 2018 that Lomachenko would have his next fight at lightweight. Arum stated he was unable to make unification fights at super featherweight against WBC champion <a href="/wiki/Miguel_Berchelt" title="Miguel Berchelt">Miguel Berchelt</a> and WBA titleholder <a href="/wiki/Alberto_Machado" title="Alberto Machado">Alberto Machado</a> which was the main reason for the move up.
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Linares">Lomachenko vs. Linares</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Linares"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Jorge_Linares_vs._Vasiliy_Lomachenko" title="Jorge Linares vs. Vasiliy Lomachenko">Jorge Linares vs. Vasiliy Lomachenko</a></div>
<p>On 30 January, Arum told <a href="/wiki/ESPN" title="ESPN">ESPN</a> that negotiations had begun in December 2017 for a fight between Lomachenko and <a href="/wiki/List_of_WBA_world_champions#Lightweight" title="List of WBA world champions">WBA</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/List_of_The_Ring_world_champions#Lightweight" title="List of The Ring world champions">The Ring Magazine</a></i> lightweight champion <a href="/wiki/Jorge_Linares" title="Jorge Linares">Jorge Linares</a> after speaking to Teiken Promotions, Linares' lead promoter, with the fight to take place on either 28 April or 12 May 2018. The fight would main event an ESPN card.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>88<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>89<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Arum was pushing for the fight to take place at Madison Square Garden on 12 May 2018. The reason behind the date was explained by Arum, "May 12th is an extraordinarily important date for ESPN programming. It's right in the middle of the basketball playoffs." Carl Moretti called Eric Gomez of Golden Boy informing them of the date. Gomez stated they were happy with the fight, however the date of 12 May was not a good date for them, as they already had plans for that date. HBO would likely air the pay-per-view replay of <a href="/wiki/Gennady_Golovkin" title="Gennady Golovkin">Gennady Golovkin</a> vs. <a href="/wiki/Canelo_%C3%81lvarez" title="Canelo lvarez">Canelo lvarez</a> rematch, along with a live bout.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>90<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>91<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 17 February, Gomez stated the fight was not called off and Arum would need to be more flexible with the date as Golden Boy accepted Arum's terms that the fight would take place in New York.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>92<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 13 March, <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times" title="Los Angeles Times">Los Angeles Times</a> confirmed that terms had been agreed between both sides. The agreement was reached after ESPN agreed to televise the fight at 8 p.m. ET/5 p.m. PT, so it would broadcast before HBO's telecast on the same day. Madison Square Garden in New York City was confirmed as the venue.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>93<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>94<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 21 March, the fight was officially announced.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>95<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> WBO president Francisco Valcarcel told Lomachenko, regardless of result, he would have 10 days to decide on whether he would return to super featherweight and defend his WBO or vacate.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>96<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Both boxers weighed in 134.6 pounds.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>97<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In front of 10,429 in attendance, Lomachenko survived a knockdown in round 6 to win via TKO in round 10 after a perfectly placed liver shot to claim the WBA (Super) and <i>The Ring</i> lightweight titles. In doing so he became the fastest fighter ever to win titles in 3 different weight classes (only 12 professional fights) shattering the previous record of 20 held by <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Fenech" title="Jeff Fenech">Jeff Fenech</a>. Lomachenko wore Linares down with his fast shots through the first 9 rounds, before finishing the fight in round 10. Linares slowly beat the count but looked too hurt to continue. Referee Ricky Gonzalez stopped the fight at 2 minutes, 8 seconds of round 10. The loss snapped Linares' 13-fight win streak.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>98<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>99<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> At the time of stoppage, two judges had each fighter ahead 8684 on their respective scorecards and the third judge Julie Lederman had it 8585 even.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>100<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> After the fight, Lomachenko said, "It was a great fight. That right hand [that knocked me down], it was a great punch. It happens. I prepared for the last few rounds, and my father [and trainer Anatoly Lomachenko] told me, 'You need to go to the body.' Linares is a great champion, and the fight was good for the fans and everybody." Speaking of the knockout punch, Linares said it was 'perfectly landed.' De La Hoya also congratulated Arum on the fight and told Arum it was good experience working together. According to CompuBox Stats, Linares landed 207 of 739 punches thrown (28%), this included 139 power punches landed and a total amount of 77 body shots landed. Lomachenko landed 213 of 627 punches thrown (34%), with 112 jabs.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>101<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>102<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> For the fight, Linares was paid a career high $1 million, with Lomachenko receiving a $1.2 million purse.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>103<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The card averaged 1,024,00 viewers.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>104<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight itself averaged 1,439,000 viewers and peaked at 1,749,000 viewers, making it the most-watched boxing fight on cable television in 2018.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>105<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 23 May, Lomachenko officially vacated his WBO super featherweight title.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>106<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Pedraza">Lomachenko vs. Pedraza</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Pedraza"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>After winning the WBA (Super) and The Ring lightweight titles, promoter Arum stated that Lomachenko would defend the belts on 25 August 2018 at <a href="/wiki/The_Forum_(Inglewood,_California)" class="mw-redirect" title="The Forum (Inglewood, California)">The Forum</a> in <a href="/wiki/Inglewood,_California" title="Inglewood, California">Inglewood, California</a>. A possible unification with WBO titleholder <a href="/wiki/Raymundo_Beltran" class="mw-redirect" title="Raymundo Beltran">Raymundo Beltran</a> was a likely possibility.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>107<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> After vacating his WBO title, Arum stated Lomachenko would not fight on 25 August.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>108<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> It was later revealed that earlier in the bout against Linares, Lomachenko suffered a torn labrum in his right shoulder. He underwent surgery on 30 May at the Cedars-Sinai Kerlan-Jobe Institute in Los Angeles. According to Lomachenko, the shoulder popped out and then back in during the second round. A new return date of December 2018 was targeted.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>109<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>110<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-111" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-111"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>111<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 10 July, Lomachenko revealed he would return on 25 August. However, on 31 July, his manager Egis Klimas told The Boxing Beat on <a href="/wiki/ESPN%2B" title="ESPN+">ESPN+</a>, Lomachenko would make his ring return on 1 December. In the interview, he also stated it would likely be a unification fight against the winner of the <a href="/wiki/Raymundo_Beltran" class="mw-redirect" title="Raymundo Beltran">Raymundo Beltran</a> vs. <a href="/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Pedraza_(boxer)" title="Jos Pedraza (boxer)">Jos Pedraza</a> bout, which was scheduled to be contested on 25 August.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>112<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>113<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Pedraza defeated Beltran via unanimous decision, winning the WBO title and setting up a fight with Lomachenko.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>114<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In September, <i>The Ring</i> magazine announced the unification fight between Lomachenko and Pedraza would take place on 8 December 2018 at the <a href="/wiki/Hulu_Theater" class="mw-redirect" title="Hulu Theater">Hulu Theatre</a> in New York City.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>115<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For the first time as a professional, Lomachenko unified in a weight division as he beat Pedraza via unanimous decision to retain his WBA (Super) title and claim Pedraza's WBO lightweight title, before a sellout crowd of 5,312. Three judges scoring the bout 119107, 117109, and 117109 in Lomachenko's favour. By mid-fight Lomachenko looked to have a solid lead on the cards, but the fight seemed closer in the ring. It was during the championship rounds where the fight came alive. Round 10 was arguably Pedraza's best as he landed a hard right hand to Lomachenko's body. He followed up with a few more bodyshots. Round 11, which was the round of the fight, saw Lomachenko come out quick and land a total of 42 power shots, his busiest round of the fight. In the middle of the round, Lomachenko shook Pedraza following a left hand, which eventually followed with a right hand to the body, dropping Pedraza. Although he beat the count, Pedraza was dropped a second time with over 10 seconds to go following a left to the body. Again, Pedraza beat the count and survived the round. Pedraza used the final round to stay out of reach and take Lomachenko the 12 round distance. The fight ended Lomachenko's 8-fight stoppage streak, in which he saw four consecutive opponents retire on their stool in between rounds.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>116<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> According to CompuBox stats, Lomachenko landed 240 of 738 punches thrown (33%), and Pedraza landed a very low 111 of his 931 punches thrown (12%). 506 of Pedraza's shots thrown where jabs in which only 31 landed. Lomachenko landed 158 power punches throughout the fight.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>117<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the post-fight interview, Lomachenko credited Pedraza as being a tough and tricky fighter, which is why he couldn't score the stoppage victory. He added, "It was my dream to unify titles. It was my next goal. I can now focus on my next chapter." Pedraza was happy with his performance and that he went "12 rounds with the best fighter in the world." He thought the fight was close up until round 11. Arum stated Lomachenko only wanted challenges going forward and would likely next fight in May 2019.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>118<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>119<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> The fight averaged 2,013,000 viewers, making it the second most-watched boxing match on American cable or network television in 2018. The fight peaked over 2.1 million viewers and the entire ESPN telecast averaged 1,865,000 viewers.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-120" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-120"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>120<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko was guaranteed a purse of $1 million, rising to $2 million and Pedraza was guaranteed $350,000, potentially earning closer to $1 million.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>121<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Crolla">Lomachenko vs. Crolla</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Crolla"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Vasiliy_Lomachenko_vs._Anthony_Crolla" title="Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Anthony Crolla">Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Anthony Crolla</a></div>
<p>Top Rank president Todd duBoef announced Lomachenko would return to the ring on 12 April 2019 at the <a href="/wiki/Staples_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Staples Center">Staples Center</a> in Los Angeles, headlining Friday night Top Rank Boxing on ESPN. With <a href="/wiki/Richard_Commey" title="Richard Commey">Richard Commey</a> and <a href="/wiki/Isa_Chaniev" title="Isa Chaniev">Isa Chaniev</a> set to fight for the vacant <a href="/wiki/List_of_IBF_world_champions#Lightweight" title="List of IBF world champions">IBF lightweight title</a>, it was highly likely that the winner would fight Lomachenko in what would be Lomachenko's second unification fight. Top Rank intended to finalize the deal with promoter <a href="/wiki/Lou_DiBella" title="Lou DiBella">Lou DiBella</a>, which would see Commey vs. Chaniev take place on 2 February 2019 at the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Center_at_The_Star" title="Ford Center at The Star">Ford Center</a> in <a href="/wiki/Frisco,_Texas" title="Frisco, Texas">Frisco, Texas</a>.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-122" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-122"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>122<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> By the end of January 2019, purse bids for Lomachenko vs. <a href="/wiki/Anthony_Crolla" title="Anthony Crolla">Anthony Crolla</a> were pushed back two days to 6 February 2019 with the minimum bid being $150,000.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-123" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-123"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>123<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Commey defeated Chaniev to become the new IBF lightweight champion, however picked up a hand injury during the fight. His promoter Lou DiBella advised Top Rank, Commey would be out of training for a minimum of two months. This prompted Top Rank to start searching for a new opponent for Lomachenko.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-124" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>124<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> On 20 February, it was announced that Lomachenko would defend his WBA (Super), WBO and <i>The Ring</i> titles against Crolla at the <a href="/wiki/Staples_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Staples Center">Staples Center</a> in <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angeles</a> on 12 April 2019. The bout, including the full undercard would be streamed live and exclusive on <a href="/wiki/ESPN%2B" title="ESPN+">ESPN+</a>, to mark the one year anniversary of the streaming service. The bout would mark Crolla's first time fighting in the US, having only fought once previously outside of his native UK.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-125" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-125"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>125<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> It was reported that Lomachenko would earn $1.2 million, but guaranteed closer to $3.2 million. Crolla, who was a heavy 1001 underdog, had an official purse of $300,000 for the fight, however guaranteed more due to UK TV rights.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-126" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-126"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>126<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In front of 10,101 in attendance, Lomachenko stopped Crolla in the first minute of round 4.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>127<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> Lomachenko visibly started to out-throw Crolla during round 2. In round 3, Lomachenko became overwhelmingly dominant while forcing Crolla to spend a majority of his time against the ropes. With 11 seconds left in the round, Lomachenko's combination was interrupted by referee Jack Reiss.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-128" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>128<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> At first glance, Lomachenko, and even the crowd, thought it looked as if Reiss had stopped the fight, causing Lomachenko to celebrate by jumping on the corner ropes. However, Reiss immediately corrected the misunderstanding and forced out commissioners who had climbed into the ring, and resumed the fight after a 10-second count for Crolla although with 1 second left, the round effectively ended immediately. Between rounds 3 and 4, Reiss explained he'd not actually waved off the fight, and instead called a technical knockdown he was seen immediately pointing and saying "down". He explained he was accounting for the ropes' aid to Crolla's ability to stand, since if the ropes had been absent Crolla would've been down and it is against the rules for a fighter to have any outside support in standing throughout the entire duration of the fight, thus justifying this rarely used but sanctioned technical knockdown. Because of this, Crolla continued on into round 4 where after briefly trying to rally back he was knocked down in second 52 by a right hook to the temple. Crolla fell to the canvas face-first, unable to break his fall. After what looked to be a 3 to 4 second count by Reiss, the fight was waved off, giving Lomachenko the win and retaining his sanctioned belts. Crolla was unable to participate in the post-fight interviews, but did not decide to immediately go to hospital.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-129" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-129"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>129<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>130<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-131" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>131<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> According to CompuBox Stats, Lomachenko landed 72 of 249 shots (29%), and Crolla landed only 12 of his 96 thrown (13%), this included 7 power shots, compared to Lomachenko's 58 power shots.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>132<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the post-fight press conference, Lomachenko said he thought it was a clear waving of the fight by Reiss, who had his back to Lomachenko and entered the exchange in a manner intent on protecting Crolla.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-133" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-133"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>133<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id="Lomachenko_vs._Campbell">Lomachenko vs. Campbell</h4><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Vasiliy_Lomachenko&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Lomachenko vs. Campbell"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320" /><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Vasiliy_Lomachenko_vs._Luke_Campbell" title="Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Luke Campbell">Vasiliy Lomachenko vs. Luke Campbell</a></div>
<p>Lomachenko faced fellow 2012 Olympic gold medallist <a href="/wiki/Luke_Campbell_(boxer)" class="mw-redirect" title="Luke Campbell (boxer)">Luke Campbell</a> on 31 August 2019, at <a href="/wiki/The_O2_Arena" title="The O2 Arena">The O2 Arena</a> in London in front of a sold-out crowd of over 18,000. Lomachenko retained the WBA, WBO and The Ring lightweight titles, and gained the vacant WBC lightweight title by defeating Campbell by unanimous decision.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-134" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-134"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>134<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> He was in fine form, winning by 119108 on two judges' cards, and 118109 on the other. Despite being a heavy underdog, Campbell started well and took the first round. Lomachenko soon found his groove, however, and almost had Campbell down in the 5th round but for the bell. Campbell took more shots in round 6, but fired back and the fight remained competitive. Lomachenko knocked down Campbell in the 11th round after a series of body shots followed by a stiff jab. Campbell beat the count, and ultimately survived the round and the fight, receiving credit after the bout for his resilience.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-bbc.com&#95;135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc.com-135"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>135<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> In his in-ring interview, Lomachenko called for a lightweight unification fight with the winner of <a href="/wiki/Richard_Commey" title="Richard Commey">Richard Commey</a> vs. <a href="/wiki/Te%C3%B3fimo_L%C3%B3pez" class="mw-redirect" title="Tefimo Lpez">Tefimo Lpez</a>, who contested for the IBF title in December.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-bbc.com&#95;135-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc.com-135"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>135<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup><sup id="cite&#95;ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>136<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
</p>
